    <name>
      <text>5.2.7 (Find solutions of tan equation exact positive)</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Find all of the solutions to the equation {@eqn@} in the range \(0 < x < 360^\circ\) Give your answers as a list, e.g. if you believe the solutions to be \(x= 10^\circ\) and \(x = 20^\circ\) enter <code>[x = 10,x = 20]</code></p>
<p>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Since we have {@eqn@} we see that the value of \(\tan\) must be positive so we must have solutions in the first and third quadrants. In other words the solutions are of the form \(x\) and \(180^\circ + x\). We can obtain the solution corresponding to the first quadrant by using our calculator (or in this case you should remember it). This gives us \(x = {@soln1@}\). For the second solution we take \(180^\circ + {@soln1@} = {@soln2@} \), hence the solutions are 
\[
x - {@aa@} = {@soln1@} \mbox{ or } {@soln2@} \implies {@ta1@}
\]
and these are the only solutions in the given range</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
